Supervisor:

Ms Peiyi Chang - Department of Education, Exhibition and Information Service


Conduction of Independent research project - “NPM Digital Archive Project”: 

Application of quantitative and qualitative research methods in the museum context;

Appraisal of the newest solutions in the field of multi-media and digital technology;

Analysis of the impact of digital technology in the museum management policy;

Examination of the collection management policy of the most prominent museum in Asia;


* In April 2011, I presented the findings of my research project to the National Palace Museum staff.

Supervisors: 

Dr Mechtild Rössler - Chief of Section, Europe and North America, UNESCO World Heritage Centre; 

Ms Anna Sidorenko-Dulom - Program Specialist for Eastern, Central and South-Eastern Europe, UNESCO World Heritage Centre


Stage:

Assisting in the follow-up of state of conservation of World Heritage properties, especially for Eastern, Central and South-Eastern Europe, including preparation of reactive monitoring missions;

Assisting in the finalization of working documents, files and power points for the 34th session of the World Heritage Committee;

Assisting in the implementation of the Astronomy and World Heritage Thematic Initiative;

Assisting during the meetings with the representatives of the Advisory Bodies ICOMOS, ICCROM and IUCN;

Conducting archival researches and preparing summaries and reports concerning the state of conservation of World Heritage properties in Eastern and South-Eastern Europe;

Collecting and analyzing statistical data and complete the Gender Indicator Table used to assess gender balance at workshops, seminaries and expert meetings organized by UNESCO in 2010;

Acting as representative of Chief of Section at the meeting for the official presentation of the website of the World Heritage property of the Fortifications of Vauban;

Presenting a study on the deletion of the World Heritage property of Dresden Elbe Valley from the World Heritage List


Professional Skills Gained:

Greater understanding of World Heritage issues;

Understanding of international legal framework and regulations concerning heritage;

Administrative skills concerning the management of World Heritage properties;

Ability to work with UNESCO database and classification systems;

Research skills pertaining to UNESCO World Heritage Centre archival material;

Analysis of statistical data;

Secretarial and organizational skills;
